1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:01,613
Just give it another minute or so.

2
00:00:16,510 --> 00:00:16,931
Very good.

3
00:00:17,231 --> 00:00:18,251
So I'll begin.

4
00:00:19,914 --> 00:00:27,522
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

5
00:00:28,263 --> 00:00:49,996
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

6
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,164
I was going to tackle this question of

7
00:00:55,363 --> 00:00:58,646
The Precepts, which was, let me see if I can find the question.

8
00:01:00,207 --> 00:01:05,692
Are all stages of the Eightfold Path equally important?

9
00:01:06,733 --> 00:01:08,915
I might get around a little bit to that.

10
00:01:09,617 --> 00:01:18,685
But I came across a couple of interesting little articles here, which, letters actually, which you might be interested in.

11
00:01:19,266 --> 00:01:23,969
So this one is written by a man called Darrell Davis from Denbighshire.

12
00:01:24,793 --> 00:01:36,289
And he says, as well as being 66 and in poor health, I also have three sisters in the at-risk category for coronavirus.

13
00:01:36,308 --> 00:01:38,171
I therefore feel qualified to say this.

14
00:01:39,272 --> 00:01:50,768
We are demolishing our economy and small businesses and wasting many billions of pounds to protect an at-risk category comprising about 1% of the population.

15
00:01:52,030 --> 00:01:57,335
The science suggests that the rest of us may get a mild form of virus but will recover.

16
00:01:58,257 --> 00:02:03,382
The best estimate states that 250,000 people will lose their lives.

17
00:02:04,504 --> 00:02:07,867
This accounts for less than half of 1% of the population.

18
00:02:09,189 --> 00:02:09,930
You see where he's going?

19
00:02:09,971 --> 00:02:13,514
This is extremely sad and awful for those affected.

20
00:02:13,814 --> 00:02:17,639
But while governments should be caring, they must also be pragmatic.

21
00:02:18,599 --> 00:02:21,783
Many of these people, including myself,

22
00:02:21,967 --> 00:02:24,670
will succumb to something else in the next few years.

23
00:02:25,693 --> 00:02:28,396
How can we justify the impact of this path?

24
00:02:29,217 --> 00:02:38,171
We're spending effectively 1.2 million per expected death on people whose life will be taken soon anyway.

25
00:02:38,973 --> 00:02:47,086
Yet we cannot find the tens of thousands of pounds, only tens of thousands, for specialist cancer treatment for much younger people.

26
00:02:47,987 --> 00:02:50,151
It will take years to recover from this regression.

27
00:02:53,016 --> 00:02:57,721
I'm just wondering what your comment might be on that, if there's any coming through.

28
00:03:04,828 --> 00:03:11,834
Just while you're thinking about that, there's somebody replied to an article that the journalist Matthew Paris had written.

29
00:03:12,433 --> 00:03:20,842
He appears to feel that younger citizens should be allowed to continue their lives almost as normal and that over 70s should be sacrificed.

30
00:03:21,262 --> 00:03:21,943
Say no.

31
00:03:22,969 --> 00:03:25,293
I suggest he completely misses the point.

32
00:03:25,453 --> 00:03:30,879
If the over-70s contract the virus, they will obviously take up valuable capacity in the NHS.

33
00:03:31,501 --> 00:03:42,234
However, without some restrictions on the less vulnerable, the very nature of their lifestyles is likely to spread the disease, infecting a high percentage of the population, young and low.

34
00:03:43,175 --> 00:03:48,943
As a member of the over-70s group, I realise that we are more expendable.

35
00:03:49,581 --> 00:03:56,108
The facts, however, are that without restrictions on everyone, the consequences for the country could be catastrophic for us all.

36
00:03:56,568 --> 00:03:59,811
So you have an opposite view there.

37
00:03:59,830 --> 00:04:06,597
Actually, when I looked at the death toll for coronavirus, most of them are over 75.

38
00:04:07,717 --> 00:04:09,280
See, so I'm all right.

39
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:10,820
I'm only 73.

40
00:04:11,080 --> 00:04:17,906
I just see if there's any indifference is the near enemy of equanimity.

41
00:04:17,927 --> 00:04:18,728
That's good, yeah.

42
00:04:20,834 --> 00:04:22,475
It reminds me of Boris Johnson.

43
00:04:22,495 --> 00:04:23,136
Yes, that's right.

44
00:04:23,156 --> 00:04:25,678
That was the herd immunity business.

45
00:04:25,959 --> 00:04:27,680
Yeah, let's everybody have it.

46
00:04:28,161 --> 00:04:29,843
And then eventually everybody's OK.

47
00:04:30,783 --> 00:04:32,105
Yes, young people are dying.

48
00:04:32,185 --> 00:04:32,745
That's true.

49
00:04:33,266 --> 00:04:35,528
It's very occasional, though.

50
00:04:35,990 --> 00:04:39,713
It's not the same rate as the old.

51
00:04:40,834 --> 00:04:44,639
And then it says people are living to 100 nowadays.

52
00:04:45,019 --> 00:04:45,660
That's true enough.

53
00:04:47,345 --> 00:05:00,367
Somebody reckons that this elderly man who's saying that they should, you know, they should expect, they should allow over 70s to get ill is not compassionate.

54
00:05:02,930 --> 00:05:03,632
Yeah, that's right.

55
00:05:04,052 --> 00:05:11,406
That was the one young boy I read of, this young boy in Brixton who died yesterday.

56
00:05:11,505 --> 00:05:12,086
He was only 13.

57
00:05:15,069 --> 00:05:21,617
Anyway, you can see there are varying views and opinions as to how the government ought to have reacted.

58
00:05:24,783 --> 00:05:35,235
But, of course, the more cynical reaction to this has been, you know, governments moving towards authoritarianism.

59
00:05:35,956 --> 00:05:40,862
And even in Europe there, this fellow in Hungary, what's his name?

60
00:05:41,564 --> 00:05:42,446
I had it somewhere.

61
00:05:42,625 --> 00:05:43,326
I knew I'd forget.

62
00:05:43,466 --> 00:05:44,367
Viktor Orban.

63
00:05:45,074 --> 00:05:47,355
He's basically become a dictator.

64
00:05:47,757 --> 00:05:53,923
He can govern now without any restriction on his authority or, in fact, any criticism.

65
00:05:54,363 --> 00:05:58,168
You can get to jail for five years if you don't agree with what they're doing or write about it.

66
00:06:00,310 --> 00:06:06,836
And it's interesting because, you know, we thought the EU, Brussels, was all powerful.

67
00:06:07,257 --> 00:06:11,122
But actually, when it comes down to nation states, they eventually can do what they want.

68
00:06:11,963 --> 00:06:12,903
You can't do anything about it.

69
00:06:16,023 --> 00:06:21,451
because it's a very small country, Hungary, and they're absolutely paranoid about being swamped by immigrants.

70
00:06:21,531 --> 00:06:24,615
I did hear a funny story, though.

71
00:06:25,216 --> 00:06:33,728
There's a nun I know from the Czech Republic, and the Czechs also don't want any immigrants whatsoever.

72
00:06:34,470 --> 00:06:43,362
And this businessman, he actually set up a few jobs for the immigrants coming through Czechoslovakia.

73
00:06:44,541 --> 00:06:45,622
But nobody wants to stay.

74
00:06:45,663 --> 00:06:47,105
Everybody wants to go to Germany.

75
00:06:49,307 --> 00:06:51,329
So that was a bit of a downer.

76
00:06:56,836 --> 00:07:01,600
See anything else?

77
00:07:01,620 --> 00:07:01,982
Oh, yes.

78
00:07:02,201 --> 00:07:05,586
A neighbor here celebrated a 102nd birthday.

79
00:07:05,766 --> 00:07:09,410
He was born in 1918 when the Spanish flu.

80
00:07:09,930 --> 00:07:12,252
We're reminded of the Spanish flu in 1918.

81
00:07:15,220 --> 00:07:25,673
Oh, somebody's got a husband's friend who is 46 and is critical now, but has no underlying conditions.

82
00:07:27,735 --> 00:07:28,918
Bring back Gordon Brown.

83
00:07:33,442 --> 00:07:36,026
I don't know why he would have done that.

84
00:07:36,047 --> 00:07:42,175
So anyway, I thought you'd be interested in that little article.

85
00:07:43,375 --> 00:07:44,737
Now,

86
00:07:46,574 --> 00:07:52,882
It's, uh, of course the, um, uh, what this brings up for us is this denial of death.

87
00:07:54,024 --> 00:07:57,067
And, um, what we, what do we mean by the denial of death?

88
00:07:57,086 --> 00:07:59,149
Everybody knows they're going to die one way or the other.

89
00:07:59,831 --> 00:08:02,194
It's the, uh, it's not facing it.

90
00:08:02,213 --> 00:08:05,778
It's not turning round to find a relationship with death.

91
00:08:07,060 --> 00:08:09,963
Uh, and that brings about this fear, this running away from it.

92
00:08:10,865 --> 00:08:11,586
And, uh,

93
00:08:12,139 --> 00:08:18,846
You can see that constantly in the way that the society has become so risk averse.

94
00:08:19,127 --> 00:08:20,807
It's just become absolutely ridiculous.

95
00:08:20,908 --> 00:08:23,391
I came across this when we put the block up.

96
00:08:24,031 --> 00:08:33,961
I mean, all the windows, all the windows that look out from a height, you can't open more than six or seven inches, you know, just in case somebody jumps out of them.

97
00:08:34,601 --> 00:08:37,304
Well, I mean, that's all very fair.

98
00:08:37,345 --> 00:08:39,767
But I mean, you know, it's like a meditation center.

99
00:08:40,186 --> 00:08:46,131
And I was arguing to them that these rules and regulations are not statutory.

100
00:08:46,511 --> 00:08:47,293
They're advice.

101
00:08:47,613 --> 00:08:53,658
And you're supposed to safeguard a building according to the purpose of it.

102
00:08:53,719 --> 00:08:58,504
So obviously, if you had children, then you put up all sorts of necessary safeguards.

103
00:08:59,745 --> 00:09:03,668
But I told him that we were completely sane meditators, 100%.

104
00:09:03,970 --> 00:09:09,315
Not a single person comes here who's suicidal or anything like that, I said.

105
00:09:09,802 --> 00:09:13,989
Anyway, he was a young fellow and he wasn't going to take any chances.

106
00:09:16,011 --> 00:09:31,437
But on that point and this ability of this fear of death, just to show you a difference in the way people have reacted way back in the

107
00:09:31,942 --> 00:09:44,238
In the 80s, when I was at the Birmingham Buddhist Vihara, we laid a new path from the door to the gate and very stupidly lay a pavement on top of another.

108
00:09:44,479 --> 00:09:47,283
So that was about a gap of a couple of inches, that's all.

109
00:09:48,043 --> 00:09:54,371
And one dark evening, you could never have seen it, one dark evening, a woman came, tripped over it and broke a nose.

110
00:09:55,128 --> 00:09:59,394
So, of course, when she told us that, we said, look, we've got public liability.

111
00:09:59,695 --> 00:10:03,159
Why don't you claim and we'd look after it?

112
00:10:03,921 --> 00:10:04,621
And she wouldn't.

113
00:10:04,701 --> 00:10:05,744
She wouldn't claim at all.

114
00:10:06,845 --> 00:10:17,120
Many years later, in the year 2001, something like that, I was asked to go to a group of depressives.

115
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:19,202
It was a depressive support group.

116
00:10:20,004 --> 00:10:21,826
And there were about 30 people in the room.

117
00:10:22,870 --> 00:10:30,022
It's a bit of a downer because it seemed as though all they were doing was making each other more depressed by telling each other how depressed they were.

118
00:10:30,602 --> 00:10:32,225
And there was one guy there who wasn't.

119
00:10:32,245 --> 00:10:34,750
And he was full of life and full of vim, you know.

120
00:10:35,150 --> 00:10:37,315
And you could see one or two people were snarling.

121
00:10:40,080 --> 00:10:43,225
I didn't think the atmosphere was very supportive.

122
00:10:43,745 --> 00:10:51,878
Anyway, the man who was running it, he gave his life story for the day, how he'd been during the week.

123
00:10:52,379 --> 00:10:55,043
And he said he'd been walking on a pavement and he tripped up.

124
00:10:56,044 --> 00:11:00,533
And he'd hurt his knee or something, you know, nothing particularly serious, anything like that.

125
00:11:01,053 --> 00:11:06,722
So he decided to claim from the local government to sue them.

126
00:11:07,504 --> 00:11:10,308
And they said he didn't have grounds to sue them at all, you see.

127
00:11:10,693 --> 00:11:13,817
And then he said, I got very angry about that.

128
00:11:14,238 --> 00:11:15,278
And then I got depressed.

129
00:11:17,322 --> 00:11:21,746
So you see, there's various attitudes out there in society.

130
00:11:23,528 --> 00:11:27,212
But this whole problem of denial of death.

131
00:11:28,514 --> 00:11:32,359
See, the Buddha gives us an exercise which you can try.

132
00:11:32,399 --> 00:11:36,344
It's extremely powerful, extremely powerful, because I've done it myself.

133
00:11:36,443 --> 00:11:37,225
I know what I'm talking about.

134
00:11:38,115 --> 00:11:44,086
And he's talking to certain monks who are practicing contemplation of death.

135
00:11:45,089 --> 00:11:53,965
And as he goes through, I'm just paraphrasing now, one monk will say, I have set myself up.

136
00:11:54,248 --> 00:12:04,480
you know, as an imaginary point that when I finish this three-month retreat, three-month seclusion, I'm going to die.

137
00:12:04,961 --> 00:12:08,566
And I'm sort of, as I approach it, I'm getting the feel of death, you see.

138
00:12:08,746 --> 00:12:09,768
The Buddha says, no, no, no.

139
00:12:09,788 --> 00:12:12,672
He says, that's not how you practice the contemplation of death.

140
00:12:13,312 --> 00:12:23,765
And then as he goes along to different monks, the time gets shorter and shorter until somebody says, you know, I'm sitting here contemplating that I might die during the night, something like that.

141
00:12:24,707 --> 00:12:28,293
And he says, no, no, no, that's not the way to contemplate death.

142
00:12:28,312 --> 00:12:36,462
He says, you have to contemplate death by recognizing as you breathe that every half breath you could die, right?

143
00:12:36,503 --> 00:12:38,885
You've got to bring it right up in front of your face.

144
00:12:38,966 --> 00:12:46,316
You've got to really recognize that we're on a tightrope and that you can fall off any moment, any time.

145
00:12:46,917 --> 00:12:54,647
And if you really work on that for a few minutes, a few seconds, and really, really convince yourself how fragile death

146
00:12:54,863 --> 00:13:00,453
life is, then you begin to get that contact with the fear of death.

147
00:13:01,134 --> 00:13:05,143
Now, this fear of death is a measure, of course, of our deluded self.

148
00:13:05,423 --> 00:13:06,264
I mean, that's what it is.

149
00:13:07,187 --> 00:13:09,451
The Buddha would not have had any fear of death.

150
00:13:10,753 --> 00:13:16,904
In fact, there are various one or two tales of the Arahats who died.

151
00:13:17,509 --> 00:13:19,633
And they died quite, quite peacefully.

152
00:13:21,355 --> 00:13:24,359
Perhaps the most dramatic one was a man called Dabba.

153
00:13:24,379 --> 00:13:32,208
Dabba was a Malian local ethnic group just north of the Ganges Plain.

154
00:13:32,970 --> 00:13:36,193
And he had certain abilities.

155
00:13:37,775 --> 00:13:40,278
And one of them you'll all know from E.T.

156
00:13:40,840 --> 00:13:44,985
He had a control, it seems, over the fire element, over heat.

157
00:13:45,352 --> 00:13:55,092
And when he became liberated, he said to the Buddha, would he mind if he just took care of lodgings in the monastery?

158
00:13:55,883 --> 00:13:57,004
That's fine, you see.

159
00:13:57,184 --> 00:14:04,375
So it says that as the monks came in, he would ask them what they wanted to study or something like that, and he would put them in various sections.

160
00:14:04,394 --> 00:14:20,798
So the people who wanted to know, to study the Vinaya, the rule, he'd put them with those people, the ones who studied Dharma with those people, and the ones who meditated with those, and he would put the athletic ones on another side, which is just a nice way of saying that they're just messing about.

161
00:14:22,461 --> 00:14:23,022
And

162
00:14:23,456 --> 00:14:31,085
He could, if they came late at night, he could show them the way to their lodgings by the light at the end of his finger.

163
00:14:33,607 --> 00:14:38,894
Now, these days, we don't believe things like that, but you'd be surprised.

164
00:14:38,913 --> 00:14:44,801
And it seems as though when he died, he just rose up in the air and exploded into light.

165
00:14:45,421 --> 00:14:46,763
That's how it's described.

166
00:14:49,065 --> 00:14:53,429
So that's just a little story, just to keep you happy.

167
00:14:54,034 --> 00:15:14,782
This fear of death, you see, is something that we can, you know, because it's all around us at the moment, people are quite paranoid about it, is to recognize that it really drives us to paranoia, to unrealistic fears.

168
00:15:15,663 --> 00:15:20,429
I mean, here in Shropshire, there's only about, I think it was about 200 cases.

169
00:15:20,570 --> 00:15:22,152
In Powys, I think it's about the same.

170
00:15:22,739 --> 00:15:29,147
So although we have to be careful, it's really getting in touch with that sense of fear.

171
00:15:29,567 --> 00:15:39,318
There's a really good time to do it, especially if you're living in places where there's quite a lot of cases like London, Birmingham, Manchester, places like that.

172
00:15:40,440 --> 00:15:41,240
And that's what you do.

173
00:15:41,280 --> 00:15:47,609
You just sit there and you breathe and you just keep saying in one way or the other, death can come now.

174
00:15:49,530 --> 00:15:51,413
Breathing out, death can come now.

175
00:15:53,907 --> 00:15:56,010
It's just getting used to the fear of death.

176
00:15:56,130 --> 00:15:59,116
And now the problem isn't the fear of death itself.

177
00:15:59,278 --> 00:16:00,259
It's the fear of fear.

178
00:16:00,360 --> 00:16:01,682
That's what's causing the paranoia.

179
00:16:01,701 --> 00:16:03,947
It's what causes the panic.

180
00:16:03,966 --> 00:16:06,873
And it's a way of getting used to the feeling of fear.

181
00:16:07,072 --> 00:16:10,600
You know, whenever that comes up, the feeling of anxiety, of fear,

182
00:16:11,052 --> 00:16:12,653
is to sort of sink into it.

183
00:16:12,693 --> 00:16:20,764
You know, this business of, remember the Buddha in the Satipatthana discourse is always saying to get feelings in feelings.

184
00:16:20,825 --> 00:16:23,948
You have difficulty getting people to get into a feeling.

185
00:16:23,969 --> 00:16:27,913
So you've got to sit in the midst of the bonfire and feel the fear.

186
00:16:28,475 --> 00:16:30,017
See, feel the fear.

187
00:16:31,038 --> 00:16:33,860
And what you're doing is you're accustoming yourself to the fear.

188
00:16:34,522 --> 00:16:39,708
See, and that means the reaction of fear of fear is disappearing, is going away.

189
00:16:40,380 --> 00:16:47,490
And when that comes, you see, you can ask yourself, well, if I no longer fear fear, what's going to frighten me?

190
00:16:49,131 --> 00:17:02,168
And then eventually, of course, this is end game, of course, that fear disappears entirely because the fear is based on the delusion of thinking that we actually are this psychophysical organism.

191
00:17:02,188 --> 00:17:08,297
We're just this organism, but the Buddha's quite clear that there's something in us which transcends it.

192
00:17:09,778 --> 00:17:10,219
So, uh,

193
00:17:10,451 --> 00:17:12,374
Have a go at that and see how you get on.

194
00:17:13,015 --> 00:17:17,219
You can drop me an email, right, if you think it's been worthwhile.

195
00:17:17,598 --> 00:17:23,625
But I myself found it a very powerful meditation, contemplation.

196
00:17:25,386 --> 00:17:25,866
Very good.

197
00:17:36,678 --> 00:17:38,400
Some little comments here.

198
00:17:41,553 --> 00:17:45,056
In the animal world, the weakest are left to die.

199
00:17:46,097 --> 00:17:51,702
Decisions during this extraordinary health crisis will reflect our humanity or compassion or our greed.

200
00:17:53,765 --> 00:17:58,230
The problem is we don't know what happens after death.

201
00:17:58,710 --> 00:18:01,792
No, you want to stay with that, you see.

202
00:18:02,213 --> 00:18:07,118
I mean, of course, there is this teaching of rebirth, but you don't have to come to a conclusion.

203
00:18:07,179 --> 00:18:08,640
You can actually stay with that.

204
00:18:08,856 --> 00:18:11,993
with the thought that you will be utterly annihilated.

205
00:18:13,201 --> 00:18:14,406
That's where the fear is.

206
00:18:14,648 --> 00:18:18,650
That's where you'll contact the fear.

207
00:18:18,670 --> 00:18:19,153
Very good.

